# Documentation Review Rubric

This rubric defines the review criteria for the **OpenShift Virtualization Cookbook**, an Antora-based documentation project written in AsciiDoc. It ensures all documentation meets high standards of quality, accuracy, and readability.

Referenced by: `tutorial-reviewer.md`, `tutorial-master-reviewer.md`, `pr-reviewer.md`

## Review Scope

Review the provided documentation against the following 10 criteria, organized by priority:

---

## 1. Professional Language

### Requirements
- Use clear, concise, and professional technical writing
- Avoid colloquial expressions, slang, or overly casual language
- Use active voice when possible
- Be direct and avoid unnecessary filler words
- Maintain consistent tone throughout the document
- NEVER use emojis or icons in any documentation

### Check For
- [ ] Grammar and spelling errors
- [ ] Awkward or unclear phrasing
- [ ] Inconsistent terminology (e.g., mixing "VM" and "virtual machine" without purpose)
- [ ] Overly complex sentences that could be simplified
- [ ] Passive voice overuse
- [ ] First-person usage (prefer imperative or third-person)

### Examples

**Avoid:**
> "So basically what we're gonna do here is set up the bridge thingy."

**Prefer:**
> "This section configures the OVS bridge for localnet connectivity."

---

## 2. Simplicity and Clarity

### Requirements
- Explain concepts in the simplest terms possible without sacrificing accuracy
- Avoid jargon unless necessary; define technical terms when first used
- Use short paragraphs and clear sentence structure
- One idea per paragraph
- Use lists and tables to organize complex information

### Check For
- [ ] Unnecessarily complex explanations
- [ ] Missing definitions for technical terms
- [ ] Long, run-on paragraphs
- [ ] Redundant information
- [ ] Information that could be better presented as a list or table
- [ ] Concepts that assume too much prior knowledge without context

### Guidelines
- Prefer bullet points for lists of items or steps
- Use numbered lists only for sequential steps
- Break complex procedures into smaller, digestible sections
- Include "What you'll learn" sections to set expectations

---

## 3. Technical Accuracy

### Requirements
- All technical information must be accurate and verifiable
- YAML manifests must be syntactically correct and complete
- Commands must be tested and functional
- API versions must be current for the target OpenShift version (4.18+)
- Resource names, namespaces, and fields must be correct

### Check For
- [ ] Incorrect or outdated API versions
- [ ] Incomplete YAML manifests (missing required fields)
- [ ] Commands that would fail in practice
- [ ] Incorrect technical terminology
- [ ] Inconsistencies between explanation and examples
- [ ] Missing or incorrect namespace references
- [ ] Deprecated features or approaches

### Verification Checklist
- [ ] Cross-reference with official OpenShift documentation
- [ ] Verify KubeVirt and OVN-Kubernetes specifics
- [ ] Check NMState operator configurations
- [ ] Validate cloud-init syntax and patterns
- [ ] Ensure storage configurations follow best practices

---

## 4. Document Length and Readability

### Requirements

**Standard Tutorials/Guides:**
- Target read time: 15-20 minutes
- Focus on ONE specific topic or use case
- Avoid scope creep

**Reference Documents:**
- Can be longer as they serve as comprehensive references
- Must be well-organized with clear sections
- Should include table of contents for documents exceeding 30 minutes read time

### Check For
- [ ] Excessive content that could be split into separate documents
- [ ] Tangential topics that distract from the main objective
- [ ] Missing content that leaves gaps in understanding
- [ ] Appropriate use of cross-references (xref) to related content instead of duplication

### Word Count Guidelines
| Document Type | Target Words | Approx. Read Time |
|--------------|--------------|-------------------|
| Quick Tutorial | 800-1,500 | 5-10 min |
| Standard Tutorial | 1,500-3,000 | 10-20 min |
| Deep Dive | 3,000-5,000 | 20-30 min |
| Reference Guide | 5,000+ | 30+ min |

---

## 5. AsciiDoc Formatting and Linting

### Requirements
- Follow AsciiDoc best practices
- Use proper syntax for all elements
- Ensure consistent formatting throughout

### Structural Elements
- [ ] Level-1 heading (`=`) at document start
- [ ] Proper header hierarchy (no skipping levels)
- [ ] Blank lines between sections
- [ ] `:navtitle:` attribute set appropriately

### Code Blocks
- [ ] Language specified: `[source,yaml]`, `[source,bash]`, etc.
- [ ] `role=execute` for user-runnable commands: `[source,bash,role=execute]`
- [ ] Heredoc blocks (`oc apply -f - <<EOF ... EOF`) use `[source,bash,role=execute]`, not `[source,yaml]`
- [ ] Each code block contains a single command or tightly coupled pipeline (no multi-command blocks)
- [ ] Host-side commands (`oc`, `virtctl`) and guest-side commands are in separate code blocks
- [ ] Proper indentation preserved
- [ ] Output blocks use plain `----` without language tag

### Links and References
- [ ] Internal links use `xref:` syntax
- [ ] Same module: `xref:page-name.adoc[Link Text]`
- [ ] Different module: `xref:module-name:page-name.adoc[Link Text]`
- [ ] External links include `window=_blank`: `link:https://...[Text,window=_blank]`
- [ ] All xrefs resolve correctly

### Admonitions
- [ ] Appropriate use of `NOTE:`, `WARNING:`, `IMPORTANT:`, `TIP:`, `CAUTION:`
- [ ] Not overused (diminishes impact)
- [ ] Content matches severity level

### Tables
- [ ] Proper column definitions
- [ ] Header rows when appropriate
- [ ] Consistent formatting

### Images
- [ ] Stored in module's `images/` directory
- [ ] Descriptive alt text provided
- [ ] Referenced correctly: `image::filename.png[Alt Text]`

---

## 6. Document Structure

### Required Sections for Tutorials

1. **Title and Introduction**
   - Clear, descriptive title
   - Brief overview of what will be accomplished
   - Context for why this is important

2. **Prerequisites**
   - Software requirements with version numbers
   - Required access levels
   - Prior knowledge assumptions
   - Links to prerequisite tutorials
   - Version tested is inline in prerequisites (e.g., "OpenShift 4.18+ (tested on 4.20)"), not in a separate block

3. **Main Content**
   - Logical flow from simple to complex
   - Clear step-by-step instructions
   - Complete, working examples
   - Verification steps after each major section

4. **Troubleshooting** (when applicable)
   - Common issues and solutions
   - Verification commands
   - Links to detailed troubleshooting guides

5. **Summary/Cleanup**
   - What was accomplished
   - Commands to clean up resources
   - Next steps or related topics

6. **See Also** (section heading must be `== See Also`, not "References")
   - Links to official documentation
   - Related cookbook pages
   - External resources

### Check For
- [ ] Missing required sections
- [ ] Sections out of logical order
- [ ] Incomplete verification steps
- [ ] Missing cleanup instructions

---

## 7. YAML and Code Quality

### YAML Manifests
- [ ] Correct 2-space indentation
- [ ] All required fields present (apiVersion, kind, metadata, spec)
- [ ] Descriptive resource names
- [ ] Appropriate namespaces specified
- [ ] Comments for non-obvious configurations
- [ ] No placeholder values left unexplained

### Commands
- [ ] All commands are complete and runnable
- [ ] Variables/placeholders are clearly marked (e.g., `<node-name>`)
- [ ] Output examples provided where helpful
- [ ] Dangerous commands have appropriate warnings

---

## 8. Consistency

### Check For
- [ ] Consistent terminology throughout (maintain a glossary)
- [ ] Consistent formatting patterns
- [ ] Consistent naming conventions for resources
- [ ] Alignment with other cookbook pages
- [ ] Consistent use of version specifications

### Common Terminology
| Prefer | Avoid |
|--------|-------|
| Virtual machine (VM) | Virtual server, guest |
| NetworkAttachmentDefinition | NAD (spell out first use) |
| ClusterUserDefinedNetwork | CUDN (spell out first use) |
| NodeNetworkConfigurationPolicy | NNCP (spell out first use) |
| OVS bridge | openvswitch bridge |

---

## 9. Accessibility and Inclusivity

### Check For
- [ ] Images have descriptive alt text
- [ ] Color is not the only means of conveying information
- [ ] Links have descriptive text (avoid "click here")
- [ ] Complex diagrams have text descriptions
- [ ] Inclusive language used throughout

---

## 10. Build Verification

Before approving, verify:
- [ ] Document builds without Antora errors
- [ ] No broken xrefs or missing images
- [ ] Code blocks render with syntax highlighting
- [ ] Navigation is correctly updated
- [ ] Page displays correctly in preview

---

## Review Output Format

Provide feedback in the following structure:

### Summary
Brief overall assessment of the document quality.

### Critical Issues
Issues that MUST be fixed before publication (technical errors, broken functionality).

### Major Recommendations
Significant improvements that should be addressed (structure, clarity, missing sections).

### Minor Suggestions
Nice-to-have improvements (style, formatting, optimization).

### Positive Highlights
What the document does well (encourage good practices).

---

## Review Severity Levels

| Level | Description | Action Required |
|-------|-------------|-----------------|
| CRITICAL | Technical errors, security issues, broken functionality | Must fix before merge |
| MAJOR | Missing sections, significant clarity issues, incomplete examples | Should fix before merge |
| MINOR | Style inconsistencies, minor formatting issues | Consider fixing |
| SUGGESTION | Optional improvements, alternative approaches | Author discretion |

---

## Quick Reference Checklist

Use this for rapid reviews:

```
[ ] Professional language, no emojis
